title: Mourning Your Old Backpacking Life Without Kids
description:
302 Lions and Children and Bears...BACKPACKING!!!

Backpacking doesn’t end when you have kids—but it definitely changes.

In this episode, we talk about what backpacking looked like before kids versus what it looks like after. From spontaneous trips and lightweight packs to planning months ahead, carrying more gear, and rethinking risk, priorities shift in ways you don’t fully understand until you’re living it.

We share how becoming parents has changed the way we think about mileage, safety, comfort, time away from home, and even why we go into the woods in the first place. Some things get harder. Some things slow down. And some parts of backpacking become even more meaningful than they ever were before.

This isn’t about saying one phase is better than the other—it’s about acknowledging that the outdoors still has a place in your life after kids… it just looks different.

title: Uttarayan on the Road | From Gugaliya Village to North Gujarat | Backpacking India
description:
This vlog is a 2-day journey through Gujarat during one of its most beautiful festivals — Uttarayan 🪁

Day 1:
I leave Gugaliya village (Panam Dam) and travel to Anand to finally collect my drone ND filters. The road, people, and unexpected moments made the journey special.

Day 2:
From Anand, I move towards North Gujarat near Modasa — and it turns out to be Uttarayan day. Everywhere I go, the sky is filled with kites, rooftops are alive, and the energy of Gujarat is unreal.

This vlog is about slow travel, festivals found unexpectedly, and life on the road while backpacking across India.

If you enjoy raw travel, villages, culture, and real experiences — this one’s for you ❤️

title: 13 Km Hike Challenge To Day | Pamir Shimshal Part 2
description:
13 Km Hike Challenge To Day | Pamir Shimshal Part 2 

Discription 👇🏾 

Today we are heading towards Pamir.
The route from Shimshal to Pamir usually takes around five days and it can be extremely difficult for us because we have no proper knowledge of the route.

Last night was one of the most dangerous nights of this journey.

The cold was extreme  around minus -24 degrees Celsius.
We slept in the open air  without shelter and somehow managed to survive the night. It was a very tough and exhausting experience.

Now we are moving forward from here towards Second Sarai, which is approximately 13 kilometers away from this point and usually takes about five hours.

The first half of the route is relatively straight but after that the trail goes steeply uphill making it even more challenging.
This journey is especially difficult because we do not know the route and we are traveling without a guide quietly and carefully relying only on our courage and instincts.

As we move forward on foot we pass through areas that were once devastated by a massive flood in the 1990s, which caused destruction from Hunza to gilgit We will show you those flood-affected locations as well.

Beyond this point  the routes become incredibly beautiful with breathtaking views all around. hi
However beauty comes with danger — the path is full of difficulties risks and physical exhaustion.
Today’s biggest challenge is that we must reach Second Hardar without eating pushing our limits in extreme cold and harsh terrain.

description:
Mestia To Ushguli Trek | Backpacking Georgia | My Worst Mountain Day Ever | #rivercrossing  
{TVLOG[73][2]}

The Trek From Mestia To Ushguli Is The Most Popular Multi-day Hike In Georgia . It Is Not Too Long, Takes Only Three To Four Days To Finish. You Don´t Have To Be A Seasoned Trekker To Enjoy It.  Passes Through Several Valley , Mountain Pass , Traditional Svaneti Villages . The SCENERY IS BANGING . 

2Days , We Experienced Three Season In One Day . Im Fall Into River End Of The Day . Camp Right Next To Glacier Viewpoint .

Winter Backpacking trip in Eagle River Alaska
description: We went to Eagle River, Alaska and snow shoed 2 miles to a backcountry yurt. The yurt was so comfortable for a winter backpacking trip. They provided us with fire wood and the wood burning stove was perfect for keep us warm when it got to 10 degrees overnight. The views at the yurt and on the way were just amazing. We may have been cold at times but we had the most amazing time and look back on it with fond memories. This is your sign to still adventure even in winter.

description: Weaver's Needle in Superstition Mountains was thought to be a landmark for the Lost Dutchman's Gold Mine, with legends saying its shadow points to the treasure or that it holds hidden riches, attracting treasure hunters, some of whom have met tragic ends in the rugged terrain.
